# Agent Readability and Cost Rules

## Intent
Keep code structure easy for humans and agents to read, reducing analysis cost and context overhead.

## Mandatory
- Keep modules narrowly scoped and named by responsibility.
- Use clear public entry points for each package to avoid deep import discovery.
- Favor small, cohesive functions with explicit inputs/outputs.
- Keep feature folders shallow and predictable to reduce navigation/search overhead.

## Agent Efficiency Constraints
- Avoid very large files that require repeated partial reads.
- Keep related logic colocated, but avoid unrelated concerns in one module.
- Keep error handling patterns consistent so agents can infer behavior quickly.
- Prefer explicit types and contracts over implicit side effects.

## Cost-Aware Patterns
- Reuse shared utilities/contracts instead of duplicating similar logic.
- Avoid unnecessary abstraction layers that add files without reducing complexity.
- Document edge cases where behavior is non-obvious.

## Prohibited
- Hidden cross-module coupling requiring broad repository reads to understand one feature.
- Deep nested control flow that obscures operational behavior.
